    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1954-06-26T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1954-06-26T00:00:00-05:00" n="472"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d472">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">
                    <gloss target="#t_CFM1">CFM</gloss> files, lot M 88, box 169, “<persName
                        corresp="#p_CHURCHILLWS1">Churchill</persName>–<persName corresp="#p_EDENA1"
                        >Eden</persName> Visit”</note>
                <head>No. 472<lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">Memorandum by the Chairman of the Atomic Energy Commission
                            (<persName corresp="#p_STRAUSSLL1">Strauss</persName>) of a Luncheon
                        Meeting, Washington, June 26, 1954, Noon</hi>
                    <note n="1" xml:id="d472fn1">According to a notation on the source text the
                        memorandum was dictated by <persName corresp="#p_STRAUSSLL1"
                            >Strauss</persName> on June 26 after a luncheon meeting with <persName
                            corresp="#p_CHERWELLLFAL1">Lord Cherwell</persName> and <persName>Sir
                            Edwin Plowden</persName>. It was drafted on July 6.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">secret</hi>
                        <lb/>CEV SPEC–2</seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date
                            ana="#date_undated-inferred-from-document-head" calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1954-06-26">June 26, 1954</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>We have met today for a discussion of certain points raised by the Prime Minister
                    in his conversations with the President.<note n="2" xml:id="d472fn2">For a
                        record of the discussion of atomic matters on June 25, see <ref
                            target="#d469">Document 469</ref>.</note> These questions, which
                    primarily concern the <hi rend="italic">effects</hi> of weapons (notably
                    thermo-nuclear weapons) were detailed by <persName corresp="#p_CHERWELLLFAL1"
                        >Lord Cherwell</persName> and <persName>Sir Edwin Plowden</persName>. Mr.
                        <persName corresp="#p_STRAUSSLL1">Strauss</persName> explained that the
                    results (<hi rend="italic">effects</hi>) of the recent test series conducted by
                    the United States were as yet incomplete but were expected to be coming from the
                    laboratories within the next months. He stated that, pursuant to the agreement
                    initiated in November, 1953,<note n="3" xml:id="d472fn3">For documentation on
                        the agreement on the exchange of atomic information with the British,
                        initiated in November 1953, see <ref target="frus1952-54v02p2#pg_1251">vol.
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">ii</hi>, Part 2, pp. 1251</ref> ff.</note> to
                    extend the <hi rend="italic">Modus Vivendi</hi> to include the effects of
                    weapons on human beings and their environment, it was the intention of the
                    Atomic Energy Commission to volunteer the exchange of this data with the United
                    Kingdom when it was received.</p>
                <p>A further question raised by <persName corresp="#p_CHERWELLLFAL1">Lord
                        Cherwell</persName> having to do with evaluation of Soviet capabilities was
                    discussed in the light of limitations on such discussions now imposed by
                    existing statute and it <pb facs="1145" n="1097" xml:id="pg_1097"/> was agreed
                    that progress beyond the collaboration now current would need to await enactment
                    of amendments to the Atomic Energy Act of 1946. The proposed amendments had
                    earlier been discussed with <persName corresp="#p_CHERWELLLFAL1">Lord
                        Cherwell</persName>.<note n="4" xml:id="d472fn4">A further discussion on
                        atomic energy matters held on June 27, CEV SPEC–3a, is in Conference files,
                        lot 60 D 627, CF 336.</note>
                </p>
            </div>
